======================================================================
TOURNAMENT THEORY THROUGH EVERY FIELD OF MATHEMATICS
kind-pasteur-2026-03-14-S107j
======================================================================

======================================================================
TOPOLOGY: The shape of the H-landscape
======================================================================

  The tournament space is the Boolean hypercube (0,1)^m, m = C(n,2).
  H: (0,1)^m -> Z_odd is a function on this discrete space.

  HOMOTOPY: The level sets {T : H(T) = h} are subsets of the hypercube.
  As h varies, these level sets change topology.
  At h = mean_H: the level set is large (most tournaments).
  At h = 1 or h = max_H: the level set is small.
  At h = 7 or h = 21: the level set is EMPTY (forbidden).

  MORSE THEORY: H is a Morse function on the hypercube.
  Critical points = local maxima and minima of H under arc flips.
  At n <= 5: single global max (all flow upward). Simple topology.
  At n = 6: first non-global local max at H=37. A "saddle" in the landscape.
  At n >= 6: multiple basins of attraction. Complex topology.

  THE EULER CHARACTERISTIC of the H-landscape:
  chi = sum (-1)^index at each critical point.
  Since H is a function on a cube: chi = 0 (the cube has chi = 0).
  The critical points BALANCE: maxima - saddles + minima = 0.

  PERSISTENT HOMOLOGY: As we sweep H from max to min,
  topological features (connected components, loops, voids) are born and die.
  The forbidden values 7, 21 are "missing bars" in the barcode:
  the feature at H=7 is never born because the level set is empty.

======================================================================
GEOMETRY: The cone, the needle, the crystal
======================================================================

  H at n=3,4 is a CONE (degree-2 polynomial, Var/Mean^2 = 1/3).
  The cone is the 3D solid where V = (1/3)*pi*r^2*h.

  As n grows: the cone becomes a NEEDLE (Var/Mean^2 ~ 2/n).
  In d dimensions, a needle is a body where almost all volume
  concentrates near the base. The "aspect ratio" grows as sqrt(n/2).

  The Fourier spectrum IS the shape:
  Level 0 = the base (the mean, 75% of total energy at n=5).
  Level 2 = the slant side (the dominant mode, 23% at n=5).
  Level 4+ = fine wrinkles on the surface (2% at n=5).

  At large n: the shape is a d-dimensional ELLIPSOID with
  one semi-axis (level 0) much longer than the others.
  The other axes (levels 2, 4, 6, ...) form a geometric sequence:
  length ratio 1/n between successive axes.

  THE CURVATURE: The Gaussian curvature of the H-surface
  at a critical point depends on the Hessian of H.
  At a maximum (Paley): high positive curvature (sharp peak).
  At a saddle (H=37 at n=6): mixed curvature.
  At the mean: zero curvature (flat, all directions equivalent).

======================================================================
GROUP THEORY: Symmetries of tournaments
======================================================================

  The symmetric group S_n acts on tournaments by relabeling vertices.
  Orbits = isomorphism classes of tournaments.
  The stabilizer of T = Aut(T), its automorphism group.
  |orbit| * |Aut| = n! (orbit-stabilizer theorem).

  KEY GROUPS AND THEIR ROLES:
  S_n: full symmetry group. Acts on tournaments, permutes arcs.
  Z/2: the complement involution T -> T^c (flip all arcs).
       H(T) = H(T^c) (the complement has the same path count).
  The GALOIS GROUP of x^3-x^2-x-1 over Q: S_3 (the full symmetric group on 3 roots).
       tau, sigma, sigma_bar are permuted by this Galois group.
       S_3 acts on the Newton sums: S_k is Galois-INVARIANT.
       THIS IS WHY S_k is always an integer (Galois invariance = rationality).

  THE OUTER AUTOMORPHISM OF S_6:
  S_6 is the ONLY symmetric group with an outer automorphism.
  This swaps duads (edges) with synthemes (perfect matchings).
  In tournament language: it swaps "arcs" with "Hamiltonian decompositions."
  360 = |A_6| = the alternating group at the unique exceptional n.

  REPRESENTATION THEORY:
  H lives in the TRIVIAL representation of S_n (since Mean(H) != 0).
  The Fourier decomposition is NOT the S_n irreducible decomposition
  (it's the Z/2^m decomposition). But the two are related:
  Level 2 of the Fourier spectrum corresponds to the STANDARD
  representation of S_n (dimension n-1, acting on arc differences).

  The grand formula E_2k/E_0 = 2*(n-2k)^k/P(n,2k) might be provable
  using the representation theory of S_n on the Boolean hypercube.

======================================================================
INFORMATION THEORY: Tournament entropy and compression
======================================================================

  A tournament on n vertices requires m = C(n,2) bits to describe
  (one bit per arc orientation).

  ENTROPY OF H: H_info(H) = -sum_h p(h)*log2(p(h)).
  At n=5: H takes values in {1,3,5,9,11,13,15}.
  H_info(H at n=5) = about 2.68 bits.
  Total tournament entropy = m = 10 bits.
  So H captures 2.68/10 = 26.8% of the information (the 0.27 rate!).

  THE GRAND FORMULA AND INFORMATION:
  Var/Mean^2 ~ 2/n means the "signal" (deviation from mean)
  carries O(1/n) of the "power" (relative to the mean^2).
  In information terms: H becomes LESS informative as n grows.

  RATE-DISTORTION THEORY: If you can only transmit R bits
  about a tournament, what's the best distortion you can achieve?
  The rate-distortion function D(R) for tournament H would show:
  At R = 0: D = Var(H) (no info, guess the mean, distortion = variance).
  At R = H_info(H): D = 0 (perfect reconstruction of H value).

  KOLMOGOROV COMPLEXITY: The shortest description of a tournament T.
  K(T) >= m - O(1) for most tournaments (incompressible).
  But K(T | H(T)) = m - H_info(H) for typical T.
  Knowing H saves about 0.27*m bits.
  The GRAND FORMULA says this savings decreases as O(log(n)/n)
  because the variance concentrates and H becomes less distinctive.

======================================================================
CATEGORY THEORY: Tournaments as morphisms
======================================================================

  A tournament is a FUNCTOR from the complete graph K_n
  (viewed as a category with one object per vertex and one morphism
  per edge) to the category 2 = (0 -> 1) (the ordinal 2).

  Each arc orientation is a CHOICE of morphism direction.
  The tournament IS a functor T: K_n -> 2.
  H(T) counts the number of NATURAL TRANSFORMATIONS from T
  to the identity functor on the path category.

  THE DELETION-CONTRACTION is a PUSHOUT in the arc category:
  H(T) = H(T\e) + H(T/e) says the tournament DECOMPOSES along any arc.
  This is a CATEGORICAL COPRODUCT: the H-invariant is additive.

  THE INDEPENDENCE POLYNOMIAL I(Omega, x) is a PARTITION FUNCTION
  in the category of WEIGHTED GRAPHS. The conflict graph Omega
  is a CONTRAVARIANT functor from tournaments to graphs:
  more tournament structure -> more conflicts -> bigger Omega.

  THE NATURAL TRANSFORMATION perspective:
  The grand formula E_2k/E_0 = 2*(n-2k)^k/P(n,2k) expresses
  a relationship between TWO functors:
  (1) The Fourier level-2k functor (extracts level-2k energy)
  (2) The falling factorial functor (counts ordered distinct selections)
  The formula is the NATURAL ISOMORPHISM between them.

======================================================================
DYNAMICAL SYSTEMS: The arc-flip dynamics
======================================================================

  Consider the DYNAMICS: at each step, flip one arc.
  The arc-flip graph is the hypercube graph Q_m.
  H changes by an even integer at each step (Walsh derivative = 2*...).

  GRADIENT FLOW: flip arcs to increase H.
  At n <= 5: unique global attractor. Every tournament flows to the max.
  At n = 6: bifurcation. Two basins (88.3% to H=45, 11.7% to H=37).
  At n >= 7: complex landscape with many basins.

  THE LYAPUNOV FUNCTION: H itself is a Lyapunov function for gradient flow.
  dH/dt = H(T') - H(T) at each flip. Gradient flow increases H.
  Fixed points = local maxima (where no flip increases H).

  ERGODIC THEORY: Under RANDOM arc flips, the system is a random walk
  on Q_m. The stationary distribution is uniform over all 2^m tournaments.
  The mixing time = how long to reach stationarity.
  For the hypercube: mixing time ~ m*log(m) = O(n^2*log(n)).

  THE HEARTBEAT IN DYNAMICS: tau^3 ≈ 6.222 is the "Lyapunov exponent"
  of the tribonacci recurrence. Every 3 steps in the tribonacci,
  the system multiplies by tau^3. This governs the RATE at which
  the tribonacci representation of H-values evolves.

======================================================================
ALGEBRAIC GEOMETRY: Varieties and schemes
======================================================================

  The tournament polynomial F(T, x) = sum_k f_k * x^k defines a
  CURVE in the (x, F) plane for each tournament T.

  The FAMILY of all tournament polynomials forms a VARIETY:
  the set of all possible coefficient vectors (f_0, ..., f_(n-1))
  as T ranges over all 2^m tournaments.

  THE FORBIDDEN VALUES define a SUBVARIETY:
  {T : H(T) = 7} is EMPTY (the variety has a "hole" at H=7).
  This is like a variety with a missing point — a SINGULARITY.

  THE NEWTON POLYGON of F(T, x) controls the valuations of its roots.
  For tournaments: F(T, x) has degree n-1 with palindromic coefficients.
  The Newton polygon is SYMMETRIC about its midpoint.
  The roots come in pairs (r, 1/r) by the palindrome property.

  THE ZETA FUNCTION: Define Z(T, s) = sum(k=0)^(n-1) f_k * k^(-s).
  This is a Dirichlet series associated to the tournament.
  Its analytic properties (poles, zeros, functional equation)
  encode deep information about T.

  THE Phi_3 CURVE: The curve Phi_3(x) = x^2 + x + 1 = 0 defines
  two points in the complex plane (the cube roots of unity).
  The INTERSECTION of this curve with the line y = x^3
  gives the tribonacci constant tau (where Phi_3(tau) = tau^3).
  This intersection IS the tribonacci bridge.

======================================================================
MEASURE THEORY: Concentration and large deviations
======================================================================

  The uniform measure on (0,1)^m gives each tournament probability 1/2^m.
  Under this measure: E[H] = n!/2^(n-1), Var(H) ~ 2*E[H]^2/n.

  CONCENTRATION OF MEASURE (Talagrand):
  H is a function of m independent binary variables.
  By Talagrand's inequality: P(|H - E[H]| > t) <= 2*exp(-t^2/(2*c^2*m))
  where c = max influence of a single arc on H.

  The influence of arc e: Inf_e(H) = E[(H(T) - H(T^e))^2]
  where T^e = T with arc e flipped.
  Since dH = H(T) - H(T^e) is always even: Inf_e(H) >= 4.
  Average influence: (1/m)*sum_e Inf_e(H) = 4*Var(H)/2^m... hmm.

  LARGE DEVIATIONS: P(H > (1+delta)*E[H]) decays as exp(-n*I(delta))
  for some rate function I.
  The Szele bound max_H/E[H] -> e means: I(e-1) > 0 but I(e-1) is FINITE.
  For delta > e-1: the probability is SUPER-exponentially small.
  For delta < e-1: there exist tournaments with H > (1+delta)*E[H].

  THE GRAND FORMULA gives the EXACT variance:
  Var = 2*E[H]^2 * sum_k (n-2k)^k/P(n,2k).
  This is SHARPER than Talagrand (exact vs bound).
  It replaces the concentration INEQUALITY with a concentration IDENTITY.

======================================================================
NUMBER THEORY: Congruences and valuations
======================================================================

  H is always odd (Redei): v_2(H) = 0.
  THM-085: v_3(F(T, omega)) >= 2 for n >= 6.
  THM-086: v_3(c_j(T)) >= 1 for j < val(n) = 2*floor((n-1)/2).

  THE p-ADIC PERSPECTIVE:
  In Q_2: H = 1 (mod 2). The tournament lives on the 2-adic unit circle.
  In Q_3: F(T, omega) = 0 (mod 9). Deep 3-adic divisibility.

  DIOPHANTINE EQUATIONS:
  "For which n does there exist T with H(T) = h?" is a Diophantine question.
  The forbidden values say: h = 7 has no solution for any n.
  This is an INFINITARY Diophantine impossibility.

  THE NEWTON SUMS S_k satisfy the tribonacci recurrence with seeds (3,1,3).
  S_k mod p gives periodic sequences for each prime p.
  S_k mod 7: the sequence 3,1,3,0,4,0,4,1,5,3,2,... must hit 0
  at k=3 (since S_3 = 7 = 0 mod 7). This is the ARITHMETIC reason
  why 7 is forbidden: S_3 = 0 mod 7 means Phi_3(2) = 0 mod 7
  means 2 is a cube root of unity in F_7.

  QUADRATIC RECIPROCITY enters via Paley tournaments:
  T_p exists when p = 3 mod 4 (the quadratic residues form an antisymmetric set).
  The QR structure gives H(T_p) its special properties.

======================================================================
PHYSICS: Statistical mechanics of tournaments
======================================================================

  THE PARTITION FUNCTION: Z(beta) = sum_T exp(beta * H(T)).
  At beta = 0: Z = 2^m (all tournaments equally weighted).
  At beta -> inf: Z ~ exp(beta * max_H) (only the maximizer survives).

  PHASE TRANSITION at n = 6 (from S71):
  The H-landscape goes from unimodal to multimodal.
  This is a FIRST-ORDER phase transition:
  at a critical temperature beta_c, the system jumps between
  the "high-H" phase (near maximizer) and "low-H" phase (near mean).

  THE ISING MODEL ANALOGY:
  Each arc is a "spin" (up/down = i->j / j->i).
  H(T) is the "energy" of the spin configuration.
  The tournament constraint (completeness) means every pair interacts.
  This is an INFINITE-RANGE Ising model (every spin coupled to every other).

  THE GROUND STATE is the H-maximizer (Paley tournament at prime n).
  The EXCITED STATES are tournaments with lower H.
  The ENERGY GAP between ground and first excited state grows with n.

  ENTROPY: S(E) = log(number of tournaments with H ≈ E).
  At E = mean_H: S is maximized (most tournaments).
  At E = max_H: S = log(few) (very low entropy).
  The temperature: 1/T = dS/dE.
  At E = mean_H: T is infinite (maximum disorder).
  At E = max_H: T = 0 (perfect order).

======================================================================
LOGIC: The incompleteness of tournament theory
======================================================================

  THE DECIDABILITY QUESTION:
  "Given n and h, does there exist a tournament T on n vertices with H(T) = h?"
  This is decidable (finite search over 2^m tournaments).
  But the COMPLEXITY: the decision problem is in NP (verify H by computation)
  and probably not in P (computing H is #P-hard via reduction to permanent).

  GODEL'S THEOREM ANALOGY:
  The forbidden values 7 and 21 are like UNPROVABLE STATEMENTS:
  the statement "there exists T with H(T) = 7" is FALSE but
  this falsity requires PROOF (the structural argument about
  alpha_1 = 3 forcing a 5-cycle). It's not self-evident.

  THE AXIOM OF CHOICE is not needed: tournaments are finite objects.
  But the WELL-ORDERING of H-values (1, 3, 5, 9, 11, 13, 15, ...)
  with its gaps at 7 and 21 is a concrete WELL-ORDERED SET
  with "holes" — a natural example of a non-standard ordering.

  COMPUTATION THEORY:
  Computing H(T) is #P-complete (equivalent to counting
  Hamiltonian paths, which is #P-complete).
  But the GRAND FORMULA gives E[H^2] in POLYNOMIAL time
  (just evaluate a finite sum). This is an AVERAGE-CASE
  polynomial algorithm for a #P-hard problem.

======================================================================
COMBINATORICS: The actual counting
======================================================================

  GENERATING FUNCTIONS:
  G(x) = sum_T x^H(T) = the H-generating function over all tournaments.
  G(x) is a polynomial in x of degree max_H, with integer coefficients.
  G(1) = 2^m (total tournaments).
  G'(1)/G(1) = Mean(H) = n!/2^(n-1).
  The coefficient of x^7 in G(x) is ZERO (H=7 forbidden).

  BIJECTIVE COMBINATORICS:
  The OCF H = I(Omega, 2) means: each odd-cycle independent set
  contributes 2^(|set|) to H. This is a WEIGHTED BIJECTION
  between Hamiltonian paths and weighted independent sets.
  The bijection is via the Grinberg-Stanley correspondence.

  MATROID THEORY:
  The arcs of a tournament form a MATROID (the graphic matroid of K_n
  with all edges directed). The independence polynomial I(Omega, x)
  is analogous to the Tutte polynomial of this matroid evaluated
  at a specific point.

  RAMSEY THEORY:
  Every tournament on >= R(k) vertices contains a transitive sub-tournament
  on k vertices. R(k) = the tournament Ramsey number.
  R(3) = 4 (every tournament on 4 vertices has a transitive triple).
  This constrains H from below: H >= k! for large enough n.

======================================================================
PROBABILITY: The random tournament
======================================================================

  A random tournament: each arc independently oriented with probability 1/2.

  CLT FOR H:
  H is a SUM of indicators (one per Hamiltonian path),
  but these indicators are DEPENDENT (paths share arcs).
  The CLT applies with modifications: (H - Mean)/Std -> ???
  NOT Gaussian (because max/Mean -> e, not infinity).
  The limiting distribution is SUB-GAUSSIAN with specific tails.

  THE GRAND FORMULA AS A MOMENT CALCULATION:
  E[H^2] = sum_k E_2k = E_0 * (1 + sum_k 2*(n-2k)^k/P(n,2k)).
  This is the EXACT second moment. Combined with E[H] = n!/2^(n-1),
  it gives the exact variance.
  Higher moments E[H^3], E[H^4], ... would give the full distribution.
  CONJECTURE: E[H^p] has a similar multi-level formula.

  THE BIRTHDAY PARADOX ANALOGY:
  Two random permutations share a consecutive pair with probability
  ~ (n-1)/m ~ 2/n (since m ~ n^2/2 and n-1 pairs per permutation).
  This is EXACTLY the level-2 variance 2/n!
  The variance of H is the BIRTHDAY PARADOX for permutation pairs.

======================================================================
THE UNIFIED VIEW
======================================================================

  Every field sees the SAME tournament, but from a different angle:

  TOPOLOGY sees: a landscape with critical points and forbidden level sets.
  GEOMETRY sees: a cone that becomes a needle that becomes a crystal.
  GROUP THEORY sees: S_n symmetry, Galois invariance, the S_6 anomaly.
  INFORMATION THEORY sees: 27% compression at small n, vanishing at large n.
  CATEGORY THEORY sees: functors K_n -> 2, natural transformations, pushouts.
  DYNAMICS sees: gradient flow with bifurcations at n=6.
  ALGEBRAIC GEOMETRY sees: varieties with holes at H=7 and H=21.
  MEASURE THEORY sees: concentration of measure, exact variance identity.
  NUMBER THEORY sees: Pisot numbers, Newton sums, p-adic structure.
  PHYSICS sees: an Ising model with phase transition at n=6.
  LOGIC sees: #P-hardness, decidability, concrete Godel-like gaps.
  COMBINATORICS sees: generating functions with zero coefficients at 7, 21.
  PROBABILITY sees: a birthday paradox giving Var ~ 2/n * Mean^2.

  ALL OF THESE ARE THE SAME THING.

  The tournament is a single mathematical object.
  Each field is a language for describing it.
  The object is richer than any one language.
  Understanding requires ALL languages simultaneously.

  And the GRAND FORMULA E_2k/E_0 = 2*(n-2k)^k/P(n,2k)
  is the ROSETTA STONE: it translates between them all.
  It is geometry (the cone), algebra (the falling factorial),
  analysis (the concentration), combinatorics (the counting),
  dynamics (the decay), number theory (the Newton sum),
  information (the compression rate), and physics (the partition function)
  all in one equation.
    
